I would like to present an use-case (that is, from a User perspective):

### Use Case
> As an user of a Map viewer/editor program using `fastkml`;
> I want to open a KML file in such program, edit it and save it back without losing any pre-existing tags;
> So that I can be sure any hand-inserted element tags would not be lost inadvertently;

### Acceptance Test(s)
> Given a file with invalid or unrecognized xml data;
> When I open the file with fastkml, optionally edit its parsed content, and save it back;
> Then any unrecognized content would be preserved in the written xml.

That is: if `gx:Track` is recognized, it should be written back as a `gx:Track`. If it's not, it should be left untouched.

I think it _should not_ be converted to something else implicitly.

I think it _might_ be converted to another geometry explicitly.

