The test case [here](https://github.com/williballenthin/python-evtx/blob/fix/issue-37/tests/test_issue_37.py#L47) demonstrates how to continue processing an evtx file despite encountering an issue decoding corrupt ASCII data.

Fortunately, the issue won't be encountered until you try to parse/render the detailed XML structure of a record. This means you can try/except rendering the XML, and continue on upon error. Fields in the record header, like timestamp and record number, remain accessible; unfortunately, the event ID is stored within the XML structure.

If you must access some fields within this "corrupt" records, let's continue to discuss here. It may be tricky, but I'm confident that we can figure out a solution.


example:
```
    with evtx.Evtx('dns_log_malformed.evtx') as log:
        for chunk in log.chunks():
            for record in chunk.records():
                try:
                    print(record.xml())
                except UnicodeDecodeError:
                    continue
```

