@scottpurdy @vitaly-krugl I investigated this for a while and came up a cleaner solution that I like.

By default, when you `#include <numpy/arrayobject.h>`, it creates a static `PyArray_API` variable for that `.o` file. This variable needs to be populated with function pointers by calling `import_array`. Since this symbol is static, there's one per `.o` file that includes this header. Each of these symbols need to be initialized separately.

In my solution, I create a shared global `NTA_NumpyArray_API` variable that only has to be populated once (or never at all, if the binary never calls numpy APIs). Rather than including the `numpy/arrayobject.h` file directly, our code does `#include <numpy/py_support/NumpyArrayObject.hpp>` which handles all the `#define` flags. Each of our binaries that call numpy APIs need to call `nupic::initializeNumpy()` once.

