There is also a problem which I'd appreciate your input on though.

Because the `info.marshmallow_sqlalchemy` passes an instance as the field Type. E.g.

```python
        capacity = sa.Column(
            sa.Integer,
            info={
                'marshmallow_sqlalchemy': {
                    'field': fields.Decimal()
                 }
            }
        )
```

This means that the field is already defined. So any additional kwargs supplied will be ignored. E.g.

```python
        capacity = sa.Column(
            sa.Integer,
            info={
                'marshmallow_sqlalchemy': {
                    'field': fields.Decimal(),
                    'load_only': True
                 }
            }
        )
```

Will not have the expected result because the `load_only` is silently ignored. This would however work:

```python
        capacity = sa.Column(
            sa.Integer,
            info={
                'marshmallow_sqlalchemy': {
                    'field': fields.Decimal(load_only=True)
                 }
            }
        )
```

This will definitely seem like unexpected behaviour. I'm wondering what you think the best way to handle this would be while still allowing the support of the `fields.Nested` and `fields.List` (as these are the reason that `field` takes an instance and not a Class.

* Always ignore info kwargs if `field` is specified?
* Throw error if there are info kwargs and `field` is specified?
* Something smarter? Potentially the kwargs get applied to the `field` instance somehow.

Cheers

