Here's the answer:

```python
import graphene

def synthesize_input_container(input_object_type_cls, data):
    # pylint: disable=protected-access
    for field_name, value in data.items():
        field = input_object_type_cls._meta.fields[field_name]
        if issubclass(field.type, graphene.InputObjectType):
            data[field_name] = synthesize_input_container(field.type, value)
    return input_object_type_cls._meta.container(data)
```

for use like:

```python
def test_synthesize_input_container():
    class RelatedInput(graphene.InputObjectType):
        id = graphene.ID()

    class Input(graphene.InputObjectType):
        id = graphene.ID()
        related = RelatedInput()

    raw = {
        'id': 'input_id_1',
        'related': {
            'id': 'related_input_id_1',
        },
    }

    input = synthesize_input_container(Input, raw)

    assert isinstance(input, Input)
    assert input.id == raw['id']

    assert isinstance(input.related, RelatedInput)
    assert input.related.id == raw['related']['id']
```

It depends on whether you are using Relay as your front-end framework. If yes, then you have to. If not, then I guess you are using [Apollo](http://www.apollodata.com/)? Well, in that case, it depends on you. 

Using Relay means you need to comply your GraphQL server with [GraphQL Relay Spec](https://facebook.github.io/relay/docs/graphql-relay-specification.html). It means for example, expressing one-to-many relation like the following is illegal:

```
query {
  group {
    users {
      name
    }
  }
}
```

Instead, you should be doing:

```
query {
  group {
    users(first: 100) {
      edges {
        node {
          name
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Relay queries comes with nice paginations as shown here and a bunch of other stuff, but totally up to you whether to use it.

I think by modifying the above code using example from https://github.com/graphql-python/graphene/blob/master/docs/relay/mutations.rst, it shouldn't be too hard. Just take note that as mentioned in https://facebook.github.io/relay/graphql/mutations.htm, all the input should be included in `input` field, which is already handled automatically by relay.ClientIDMutation. So your Mutation query should be like:

```
mutation{
  createPerson(input: { firstName: "Foo", lastName: "Bar" }) {
    ...
  }
}
```

